Exercise 1

Exercise 2

Dino Dataset Plot

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Dino Dataset Correlation

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 5

Plots for All Datasaurus Datasets

ggplot(data = datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Correlations for All Datasaurus Datasets

datasaurus_dozen %>%
  group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y)) %>%
  print(13)
## # A tibble: 13 x 2
##    dataset          r
##    <chr>        <dbl>
##  1 away       -0.0641
##  2 bullseye   -0.0686
##  3 circle     -0.0683
##  4 dino       -0.0645
##  5 dots       -0.0603
##  6 h_lines    -0.0617
##  7 high_lines -0.0685
##  8 slant_down -0.0690
##  9 slant_up   -0.0686
## 10 star       -0.0630
## 11 v_lines    -0.0694
## 12 wide_lines -0.0666
## 13 x_shape    -0.0656
  • All r values are very similar to each other despite their plots being extremely different. This shows how correlation on its own can be decieving.
